A more general multivariate generalization of Theorem 1 in \cite{thakur} can now be formulated as follows.
\begin{prop}\label{thakur1-multid}
Let $g \in L^2(\mathbb{R}^d)$ be real-valued and band-limited and let $X$ be a sign-blind sampling set for ${\text{supp }} \hat{g}$. Then, up to a global sign, $g$ can be uniquely recovered from the samples $|g|(X)$.
\end{prop}
\begin{proof}
The proof follows immediately from Proposition \ref{thakur1-multid-simple}, after a simple change of variables $x \to Mx$.
\end{proof}

The sampling density required in Propositions \ref{thakur1-multid-simple} and \ref{thakur1-multid} may not be sharp. In one dimension, if $b$ is the actual bandlimit of the real-valued function $g \in L^2(\mathbb{R})$, i.e. ${\text{supp }} \hat{g} = [-b/2,b/2]$, then for any sampling rate $s \geq 1$, $g$ can be recovered up to a global sign from $\left(|g(n/(2sb))|\right)_{n \in \mathbb{Z}}$. Conversely, if $s<1$, then there exist functions $g_1$ and $g_2$ with bandlimit $b$, $g_1 \neq c g_2$ for any constant $c$, for which 
nevertheless $|g_1(n/(2sb)|=|g_2(n/(2sb)|$ for all $n \in \mathbb{Z}$, so an oversampling factor of at least $2$ is required. However, Propositions \ref{thakur1-multid-simple} and \ref{thakur1-multid} use lattices with density $2^d\Pi_{\j=1}^d s_j \geq 2^d$ if ${\text{supp }} \hat{g} = \left[-\frac{1}{2},\frac{1}{2} \right]^d$, corresponding to an oversampling factor of $2^d$, which is probably excessive. In Proposition \ref{thakur1-multid-simple}, the product argument can be applied to each of the $d!$ different permutations of the dimensions and will reconstruct the same $g$ in each case (up to a sign), suggesting that there is some additional redundancy beyond the one-dimensional case. One could also argue that unsigned sampling loses ``only'' a single bit per sample, which likewise suggests that a factor of $2$ instead of $2^d$ may suffice. However, showing this would require an approach substantially different from the one taken in \cite{thakur}.\\

There is another manner in which the density threshold can be viewed as ``not sharp'': when ${\text{supp }} \hat{g}$ does not align well with the coordinate axes, 
the critical density can depend on the lattice directions determined by the matrix $M$.
More precisely, given a compact set $F$, there can exist
several matrices $M_{\ell}$, with {\em different determinants}, 
such that $F \subseteq M_{\ell} \left[-\frac{1}{2}, \frac{1}{2}\right]^d$ but 
$F \nsubseteq M_{\ell} \left[-\frac{t}{2}, \frac{t}{2}\right]^d$ for $t<1$. 
The corresponding
lattices $X_{\ell}=(M_\ell^{\top})^{-1} D[2{\mathbf{s}} ]^{-1} \mathbb{Z}^d$ then have 
densities $2^d \det(M_\ell) \Pi_{j=1}^d s_j$; the requirement that all $s_j \geq 1$ corresponds to 
the different ``critical'' density values $2^d \det(M_\ell)$, for
the same set $F$. (Note that this
issue is not specific to whether or not the samples are signed or unsigned.)



